{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Makes Attention Sparse"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In full self-attention every token attends to every other token — a dense T×T weight matrix. Sparse attention restricts each token to attend to a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "structured subset"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " of positions. The subset is chosen so that: (1) the non-zero entries cover far fewer than T² pairs, reducing cost; and (2) any two positions can still exchange information, either directly or through a chain of attended positions across layers."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This differs from sliding-window attention, which is one specific sparse pattern. The broader sparse attention family includes strided patterns, random attention, global-token attention, and combinations thereof."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Strided sparse attention pattern and BigBird local+random+global pattern, with complexity comparison table"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Sparse Transformer: Strided and Fixed Patterns"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Child et al. (OpenAI, 2019) introduced the Sparse Transformer with two factorised attention patterns that together cover all pairwise dependencies in O(T√T) non-zero entries:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Strided attention"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": token t attends to {t, t−1, t−stride, t−2·stride, …}. With stride = √T, each token attends √T positions and any pair is covered in ≤2 hops."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Fixed (block) attention"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": tokens attend within a local block of size c, plus all tokens at the last few positions of each preceding block. The fixed positions act as summaries that any later token can access."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\n\ndef strided_attention_mask(T: int, stride: int) -> torch.BoolTensor:\n    \"\"\"Causal strided attention: token t attends to t-k*stride for k=0,1,2,...\"\"\"\n    mask = torch.zeros(T, T, dtype=torch.bool)\n    for t in range(T):\n        # local (previous 1 step)\n        if t > 0:\n            mask[t, t - 1] = True\n        mask[t, t] = True    # self\n        # strided positions\n        pos = t - stride\n        while pos >= 0:\n            mask[t, pos] = True\n            pos -= stride\n    return mask\n\nT, stride = 16, 4\nmask = strided_attention_mask(T, stride)\nprint(f'Non-zero entries: {mask.sum().item()} of {T*T} ({mask.sum()*100/T/T:.0f}%)')\n# For T=16, stride=4: ~32 of 256 = ~12%  (vs 100% for full attention)\n\ndef apply_sparse_attention(q, k, v, mask):\n    B, T, d_k = q.shape\n    scores = torch.bmm(q, k.transpose(1, 2)) / math.sqrt(d_k)\n    scores = scores.masked_fill(~mask.unsqueeze(0), float('-inf'))\n    attn = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1).nan_to_num()\n    return torch.bmm(attn, v)\n\nq = k = v = torch.randn(1, T, 32)\nout = apply_sparse_attention(q, k, v, mask)\nprint(out.shape)  # (1, 16, 32)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BigBird: O(T) with Theoretical Guarantees"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Zaheer et al. (Google, 2020) proved that combining three attention components achieves O(T) non-zero entries while remaining "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Turing complete"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and capable of simulating any function that full attention can compute:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Local windows"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": each token attends to w nearest neighbours. Provides local context with O(T·w) entries."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Random attention"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": each token attends to r randomly chosen other tokens. This is the graph-theoretic bridge: random edges make the attention graph an expander, ensuring short paths between any two positions."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Global tokens"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": g tokens attend to and are attended by all positions. Global tokens aggregate and broadcast global state, enabling O(1)-hop global communication."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\n\ndef bigbird_mask(T: int, window: int = 3, n_random: int = 2, n_global: int = 1,\n                seed: int = 0) -> torch.BoolTensor:\n    \"\"\"\n    BigBird attention mask: local window + random + global tokens.\n    n_global: first n_global tokens are global (attend everywhere).\n    \"\"\"\n    torch.manual_seed(seed)\n    mask = torch.zeros(T, T, dtype=torch.bool)\n\n    # 1. Global tokens: bidirectional, full range\n    for g in range(n_global):\n        mask[g, :g + 1] = True      # global token attends all past\n        mask[:, g] = True           # all tokens attend global token\n\n    # 2. Local causal window\n    for t in range(T):\n        lo = max(0, t - window + 1)\n        mask[t, lo:t + 1] = True\n\n    # 3. Random attention (causal: only past tokens)\n    for t in range(1, T):\n        candidates = list(range(t))          # all past positions\n        if len(candidates) >= n_random:\n            chosen = torch.randperm(len(candidates))[:n_random]\n            for idx in chosen:\n                mask[t, candidates[idx]] = True\n\n    return mask\n\nT = 32\nmask = bigbird_mask(T, window=3, n_random=2, n_global=2)\nprint(f'BigBird non-zeros: {mask.sum().item()} of {T*T} '\n      f'({mask.sum()*100/T/T:.0f}%)')  # ~20-25%\n# Full attention: T*(T+1)/2 = 528 causal entries\n# BigBird: roughly (window + n_random + n_global) * T ≈ 7 * 32 = 224 — O(T)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Longformer: Combining Local and Global"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Longformer (Beltagy et al., 2020) applies BigBird-style attention to long documents using two attention types controlled by the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "attention_mask"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tensor: 1 = local window attention, 2 = global attention. Task-specific tokens (e.g. [CLS], question tokens in QA) are given global attention."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import LongformerTokenizer, LongformerModel\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = LongformerTokenizer.from_pretrained('allenai/longformer-base-4096')\nmodel = LongformerModel.from_pretrained('allenai/longformer-base-4096')\n\n# Long document: ~600 tokens\ntext = 'The transformer architecture introduced self-attention. ' * 60\ninputs = tokenizer(text, return_tensors='pt', truncation=True, max_length=512)\n\n# attention_mask values:\n#   0 = padding (no attention)\n#   1 = local window attention\n#   2 = global attention (attends to and from ALL positions)\nattention_mask = inputs['attention_mask'].clone().long()\nattention_mask[0, 0] = 2   # [CLS] is global — aggregates full document signal\n\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    output = model(**inputs, attention_mask=attention_mask)\n\ncls_repr = output.last_hidden_state[0, 0]   # global token representation\nprint(cls_repr.shape)   # (768,) — encodes full-document context\nprint('Configured window:', model.config.attention_window)  # [512] per layer"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Sparse vs dense in practice: "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Sparse attention patterns were the dominant approach to long-context before FlashAttention made dense attention practical at longer lengths. With FlashAttention-2 and hardware improvements, many production models now use dense attention at contexts up to 128k. Sparse attention remains valuable for extreme lengths (1M+ tokens), for specialised domains (genomics, long-form documents), and for research into theoretical properties of attention. For standard LLM pretraining and fine-tuning, dense attention + FlashAttention is simpler and usually preferred."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
